First, we show that the subobject poset of P is a lattice.
  Let S and T be subfunctors of P. Then:

the meet is given by (P\wedge  Q)X = PX\cap  QX;

the join is given by (P\vee  Q)X = PX\cup  QX;

the implication is given by (P\Rightarrow  Q)X = \{x\in  PX: \text { for all }     Y\xrightarrow {f} X\in  C, \text { if } Pf(x)\in  SY \text { then } Pf(x)\in  TY\}.

In addition to those of a bicartesian closed category, a Heyting
algebra satisfies the following equations: 
x\Rightarrow  x = \top ;

x\wedge  (x\Rightarrow  y) = x\wedge  y;

y\wedge  (x\Rightarrow  y) = y;

x\Rightarrow  (y\wedge  z) = (x\Rightarrow  y)\wedge  (x\Rightarrow  z).

The construction of the bijection now demands that, for c\in  C, r\in    Rc, and p\in  Pc, we have \alpha _c(r, p) = \operatorname {ev}_c(\beta _c(r), p) =   \beta _c(r)_c(1_c, p). This defines \beta _c(r)_c, and naturality in C
  now forces, for any c\xrightarrow {f} d, 




